<TEXT>
hundreds of soviet jews the last group 
to pass through this gateway to america celebrated a passover 
dinner together in an atmosphere of joy and expectancy 
its the beginning of a new life said sovietborn rabbi 
hirsch rabiski who led monday evenings traditional seder 
the approximately 7800 soviet jews staying in the ladispoli 
area near rome are all to be resettled in the united states or 
other countries by late may 
their departure marks the end of an era in which nearly all 
soviet jews bound for the united states lived in this seaside area 
their applications handled at the main us processing center in 
rome over time ladispoli became a symbol of the hope and despair 
of soviet jewish refugees 
now the us government is handling the refugees applications 
in moscow instead of rome 
most of the arrivals in ladispoli learned little about their 
faith and culture in the officially atheist soviet union even 
though they were often persecuted for being jews monday evenings 
ceremony in a blueandwhite tent was the first seder for many 
samuel dropkin 39 was determined to get it right 
the electrical engineer carefully studied a manual in hebrew and 
russian illustrating how to prepare for the passover meal 
aided by his 7yearold daughter jane im not jana any 
more he stacked three matzo on the table covered them with a 
paper napkin and added a hardboiled egg some lettuce a slice of 
onion and a dab of horseradish 
i really feel as a jew he beamed 
during the passover meal held on the first evening of the 
holiday jews eat foods symbolizing themes of redemption and 
freedom and read from the hagada of the jews flight from egypt 
the holiday commemorating that exodus is among the most important 
for jews 
dropkin from the city of baku in azerbaijan waved a hand at 
the approximately 600 people sitting at tables piled with passover 
foods 
this picture in the soviet union is impossible he said in 
broken english this is a pleasure for us we join with our 
people 
on a stage in front of the tables rabbi rabiski patiently 
explained the meaning of the ceremony and led prayers in russian 
following his example hundreds of people stood and filled plastic 
cups with sweet lambrusco wine the first of four glasses to be 
drunk during the passover ceremony 
this is very difficult for us its the first time said 
vitaly shlimack 20 of baku at a table with his parents and the 
dropkins 
i know the jewish history but very very bad i know the 
tradition but very very bad 
only the words in our passports made us jews we had no 
culture no language no tradition nothing 
while they are in ladispoli the soviets receive religious 
instruction from jewish groups in addition to help with housing 
money and language lessons 
two usbased jewish groups the american joint distribution 
committee and the lubavitch organization sponsored mondays seder 
in the tent 
several other smaller seders were held in ladispoli and nearby 
towns with 10 rabbis flying in from the united states to help out 
most of the soviet jews have received their visas and are 
awaiting transportation arrangements medical clearance or 
confirmation that they had been matched with sponsors 
the refugees at the ladispoli tent spoke nervously about their 
new homes and the state of their english but they were thrilled 
about being able to freely practice their faith 
i am going to learn every jewish holiday here or in 
america said felix kopylenko 30 of kiev who is headed for 
chicago on april 19 he wore his baby daughters white knit cap 
because he didnt own a yarmulka or jewish skullcap 
the passover ceremony appeared to remind some of the soviet jews 
of their own flight from their homeland 
dropkin said he had been denied work and educational 
opportunities in the soviet union because he was a jew and i had 
enough 
now its very well he said brightening now its a 
celebration 
</TEXT>
