<TEXT>
as moves gather pace to restart the 
angolan peace process jonas savimbis usbacked unita rebels are 
tempting angolas marxist government with some concessions 
the rebels are offering an immediate ceasefire and conditional 
recognition of the angolan state 
the concessions announced in a statement released in lisbon on 
monday and signed by savimbi and other topranking rebel officials 
have plenty of strings attached but they could overcome an impasse 
that has thwarted peace efforts since a shaky first truce collapsed 
last summer 
they are being offered after three months of what is said to be 
the heaviest fighting in the war so far and steppedup unita bomb 
attacks in the capital luanda 
according to the statement the rebels are ready to cease 
hostilities immediately and without preconditions and would 
recognize the angolan state on the basis of accords signed before 
independence from portugal in 1975 
there was no immediate reaction from angolan government 
officials 
but while offering an immediate ceasefire in the field the 
statement said unita was determined to act with more aggression 
in luanda until a truce is sealed 
if there is no peace well hit where it hurts most the 
statement said 
the national union for the total independence of angola unita 
previously conditioned talks on a government troop withdrawal from 
positions captured in rebel heartlands in southeast angola unita 
also always had refused even to mention the possibility of 
recognition under any circumstances 
the alvor accords signed in january 1975 by unita the popular 
movement for the liberation of angola mpla government and a third 
guerrilla movement the fnla set angolan independence for november 
of that year after an interim powersharing government had been 
formed by the three parties 
but fighting broke out shortly afterward and intervention by 
the united states the soviet union cuba and south africa 
escalated the conflict to its present heights unita receives a 
reported 50 million or more in us aid annually and western 
estimates of soviet backing to luanda run much higher 
by agreeing to recognize the angolan state albeit under the 
alvor terms that dont guarantee mpla authority unita is aiming to 
persuade luanda moderates they can reopen talks without losing face 
as an extra sweetener the rebels also pledged to respect all 
accords signed over the past 15 years by the mpla government 
once free and fair elections were held in angola 
government hardliners cheered by recent military successes 
are still insisting on full recognition of the mplas singleparty 
authority and state institutions 
luandas rapid military advance in late december led to the 
capture of the strategic mavinga air base in the southeast but the 
offense has been halted mainly due to faltering food fuel and 
ammunition supplies 
also the rebels have made good promises to step up hitand run 
bush war and urban guerrilla attacks lending weight to moderates 
arguments that the conflict can only be ended by talks 
both sides are now proposing direct talks western diplomats in 
lisbon and luanda say the government prefers cape verde as a venue 
but the rebels proposed direct closeddoor contacts in lisbon 
stressing that portugal can play a pivotal role among angolans of 
all political sensibilities 
the centerright portuguese government has kept close relations 
with luanda while allowing unita to maintain a major 
representation office in lisbon that the rebels have recently 
upgraded 
but unita foreign affairs secretary toni da costa fernandes 
reaffirmed in an interview on portuguese rtp state television late 
monday that the rebels would still back president mobutu sese seko 
of zaire as mediator until a truce is agreed 
the rebel statement also suggested the superpowers play a more 
active role in finding a speedy solution 
</TEXT>
