<TEXT>
perhaps even now pregnant wasps are waking 
from their winter slumber at kennedy space center to build paper 
nests and lay eggs in the warm florida sun 
by september the eager young hatchlings will be swarming to look 
for mates the tops of 300foot launch towers built by humans for 
trips to the stars are favorite places for wasp courtship and 
frenzied lovemaking 
the swarming goes on until middecember weeks when workers at 
the center are pestered and threatened by the wasps says an 
agriculture department report scientists are trying to rig 
effective traps but admit those may take a few more years of 
research 
entomologist peter j landolt of the departments agricultural 
research service suspects the wasps mistake the tall launch towers 
for their usual mating sites trees and hilltops 
thus when the mating swarms leave nests built in bushes or on 
houses the launch towers and other manmade structures at the 
center are the tallest things around 
landolt who works for the agencys research laboratory in 
gainesville fla said thousands of male wasps lead off the mating 
ritual by swarming to kennedy facilities favored gathering places 
are around a launch pads crane and near the crane motors housing 
room 
the males search for anything that protrudes to sit on a bolt 
for example then they rub their heads and tails on the perch to 
release sex attractants or pheromones into the air to attract 
females 
they bite and wrestle trying to knock each other off the 
perches its a very competitive time and there is a prize 
we believe each male wants an ideal spot to sit and wait for 
virgin females to arrive so he can mate landolt said every 
male wants his pheromone odor to be strongest so that females will 
be attracted to him 
hundreds of female wasps lured by the scents of sexhungry 
males and the tall towers swarm to greet the thousands of suitors 
selecting the ones they desire the couples mate in midair 
requiring about a minute 
once inseminated the females fly into the crane housing room 
where they cluster together on walls to keep warm and protect 
themselves from predators or they squeeze into cracks and crevices 
the females remain there all winter living off stored body fat 
util spring when they return to the ground to build nests of paper 
they make by chewing bark from trees then they lay their eggs use 
themselves up protecting the brood and die in the fall 
meanwhile the male wasps that were successful suitors during 
the previous swarm season eventually die also having dutifully 
served their sole purpose in life the report said the 
unsuccessful males also die of course 
the space center wasp project was reported by jessica morrison 
silva of the usda agencys beltsville md staff in the current 
issue of agricultural research magazine 
officials of the national aeronautics and space administration 
asked usda two years ago for help to control the wasps so far 
landolt and colleague hal c reed have worked out what they think 
is the wasps annual mating ritual but they arent completely sure 
for one thing they have to be certain the wasps are mistaking 
launch towers for tall trees so landolt and reed plan to go into 
the everglades in search of nesting wasps in tall trees to 
corroborate the theory 
eventually they hope to isolate and reproduce the pheromones 
used by the wasps in their sex rituals with the synthetic sex 
attractants traps can be built to control the pests 
since the problem began five years ago only one nasa employee 
has been stung at the center despite the large numbers of wasps 
but just seeing a thousand or more wasps buzzing around at 300 feet 
can be hazardous by itself landolt said 
aside from the employee hazard nasa wants to ensure that the 
wasps dont enter a space shuttles electronic and mechanical 
equipment 
obviously a shuttle liftoff is an effective and quick means 
of controlling the wasp problem reed said 
but nasa wants a less drastic way of curbing the wasps between 
liftoffs 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

