a few years ago charges of police 
brutality made headlines in the border town of mcallen texas 
today residents come to a neighborhood ministation to drop off 
plates of food for officers 
sgt belinda cowan credits the smoother relations to the 
departments switch three years ago to community policing a 
philosophy that is the subject of a conference today and tuesday at 
michigan state university 
officers may patrol on foot staff a small office or drive a 
patrol car but the key to community policing is facetoface 
contact with neighborhood residents said robert trojanowicz 
director of michigan states school of criminal justice 
cowan said the results are striking 
were seeing tremendous support from citizens because were 
working together as partners she said its no longer im 
the police just the facts maam they are a part of our 
department 
about 300 cities use some form of community policing and get 
similar results trojanowicz said 
community policing advocates planned to describe at the 
conference how this decentralized form of police work which became 
popular in the late 1970s can stop drugs from overwhelming 
neighborhoods 
officers in community policing programs work in the same 
neighborhood for at least a year getting to know the areas 
problems and enlisting the help of citizens in fighting crime 
fixing up the neighborhood and other programs 
with this personalized approach to police work officers have 
more contact more communication with the public trojanowicz 
said trust is built up and information is exchanged that would 
not otherwise be exchanged and information is the lifeblood of 
police work 
community police officers try to get to the root of problems as 
in aurora colo where police had frequent reports of womens 
purses being ripped off in car breakins at a popular nightclub in 
the denver suburb 
typical police response would have been to go out and take 
reports on stolen purses over and over and never go further said 
aurora police chief jerry williams 
instead the aurora officer encouraged the nightclub owner to 
build lockers where women could safely leave their purses while 
dancing the crimes stopped 
police mobilize citizens into neighborhood watch groups 
encourage people to testify in court find out which children 
arent attending school and pressure city leaders to tear down 
dilapidated buildings that are eyesores or havens for crime 
that can mean less time for responding to minor complaints like 
barking dogs trojanowicz said adding citizens are encouraged to 
handle those things themselves 
in mcallen police received more reports of crime in the first 
year after community policing began possibly because citizens were 
more willing to file reports cowan said 
the negative rap on community policing is its public 
relations grin and wave it humors people and doesnt cure 
anything trojanowicz said the focus of the conference is to 
show it is real policing and to show it in fact can get rid of drug 
dealers 
some police fear for their safety if they spend less time in 
patrol cars and more time in direct contact with citizens but 
trojanowicz said citizens are more likely to come to the aid of an 
officer they know 
studies have shown that as officers have become more 
personalized if they are in danger its a little more difficult 
for citizens to be aloof he said he has a stake in the 
neighborhood and the neighborhood has a stake in him 
