<TEXT>
a top economic adviser to president mikhail s 
gorbachev said monday that authorities will have to overcome strong 
public resistance to push through a radical marketoriented 
economic reform program this year 
a speedy transition to a market economy will come up against 
powerful opposition deputy prime minister leonid abalkin told a 
news conference we must do it whether we like it or not 
what we must do first is to make all people understand and see 
clearly that without such a transition the country has no future 
as a highly developed great power 
as he answered reporters questions abalkin repeatedly dodged 
specifics implying that key decisions in the reform program had 
not yet been made for example he said the state must lift 
controls on prices but would not specify which prices would be 
freed or when 
he also denied reports circulating among the foreign business 
community that some form of convertible ruble would be introduced 
by this summer he said experts believe the soviet market must have 
something to sell first and it will take years before the countrys 
currency will be convertible 
several officials have suggested in recent weeks that the soviet 
union was considering a plan to provide a polishstyle shock 
therapy for the soviet economy which would boost prices 
drastically cut the value of the ruble and raise unemployment 
in december premier nikolai i ryzhkov outlined to the soviet 
congress an economic program calling for five more years of central 
planning with a gradual introduction of some elements of a market 
economy it further delayed a reform of prices which are currently 
set by bureaucrats without regard to the cost of production 
but in march just after he was given a new powerful post as 
president gorbachev said more radical economic reforms were 
urgently needed 
the reforms are being speeded up due to destabilization of the 
political system development of ethnic and regional conflicts and 
deficits in the consumer goods market abalkin said 
with the economy stalled partway between central planning and a 
market system industrial production fell 12 percent in the first 
quarter of 1990 compared with the last quarter of 1989 
unless we go over to the new methods we will deprive 
ourselves and our children of a highly developed and efficient 
economy and a powerful country where people will want to live and 
which the people will not be ashamed of abalkin said 
we will have to make sacrifices he added but there must 
be a social consensus for that 
state price committee chief vyacheslav senchagov told the 
legislature last week that among the three reform variants under 
consideration was the polish example of a crash program to create a 
maret economy 
poland hopes the abrupt transformation will keep the painful 
period short and the inflation rate has already fallen drastically 
from the tripledigit level of january 
but abalkin said the soviet government cannot count on public 
support for such a policy 
he left unsaid the fact that polands shock program was 
instituted by the new solidarityled government which replaced the 
unpopular communists last august 
