<TEXT>
lothar de maiziere the prime 
ministerdesignate proposed a cabinet on monday that includes the 
major political parties and has a peace activist as defense 
minister 
the christian democrat leader unveiled the tentative composition 
of east germanys first democratic government after negotiations 
with the nations diverse political groups 
parliament is expected to vote on nominations to the 24member 
cabinet on thursday 
agreement was reached in five days of talks with the social 
democrats who finished second to the christian democrats in east 
germanys first free elections march 18 
differences between the two main parties still exist on the pace 
and form of eventual unification with west germany including how 
much of the socialist welfare state should be retained for east 
germans who depend on food and housing subsidies 
german reunification was the main issue in the elections and 
remains the overriding priority but agreement on a cabinet clears 
a major hurdle de maizieres government would replace communist 
caretaker administrations that have run the country since the 
prodemocracy revolt in october 
a threeparty conservative alliance led by de maiziere would 
dominate the new cabinet with 14 seats the social democrats would 
have seven posts and three would go to a smaller liberal alliance 
eleven of the 24 seats actually were filled with talks to 
continue tuesday on naming the rest of the ministers 
social democrat leader markus meckel was nominated to be foreign 
minister 
the social democrats also will hold the post of finance minister 
and named walter romberg a key negotiator with bonn over the 
planned monetary union 
rainer eppelmann who leads the democratic awakening party part 
of de maizieres alliance was chosen defense minister his 
ministrys name was changed to department of defense and 
disarmament a symbolic reference to german demands for fewer 
nuclear weapons in superpower military stategy 
eppelmann a lutheran minister and peace activist who took part 
in the revolt against stalinist leader erich honecker probably 
will play a role in talks on a united germanys future role in the 
eastern and western military alliances 
leaders of the social democrats expressed satisfaction with 
mondays talks but party spokesman guenther krug said 
substantial differences that remain would be the subject of 
further negotiations 
we assume that difficult negotiations lie ahead krug said 
although de maizieres alliance won the most seats in the 
400member parliament it lacks the twothirds majority needed to 
enact constitutional changes that would allow quick unification 
with west germany 
a coalition with the social democrats would give de maiziere 
control if negotiations with that party fail he can try for 
agreements with other parties 
de maiziere supports rapid reunification of germany as does 
chancellor helmut kohl of west germany but the social democrats 
favor a more gradual process 
they also differ on the role of an east german government which 
faces severe economic problems but also is likely to be a 
shortlived transitional administration 
among issues still to be clarified are west germanys role in 
nato east germanys membership in the warsaw pact and the 
difficult question of private property 
east germans have not been allowed to own land and west germans 
have made claims on property their ancestors owned before the 
nation was divided after world war ii 
social democratic leaders want employees to share in former 
stateowned companies but the christian democrats favor complete 
sale to private owners 
the parliament elected march 18 convened april 4 and 
designated de maiziere as prime minister it also began dismantling 
the 40yearold communist system and created an office of president 
sabine bergmannpohl president of parliament was named acting 
national president and assumed her duties as head of state monday 
she urged a quick conclusion of the coalition talks installation 
of a new government and choice of a permanent president 
hanging like a cloud over the process of building a new 
political order are allegations that some members of the new 
parliament had ties to the reviled secret police of the old 
communist regime 
de maiziere has denied such allegations in his own case two 
other accused political leaders have resigned 
parliament is expected to vote on whether to form an independent 
commission to investigate the allegations the former secret police 
agency has been disbanded 
 
