<TEXT>
a philadelphia auto parts manufacturer will 
pay a 15 million fine for violations of government noise 
standards on the job the labor department said monday 
the settlement between the occupational safety and health 
administration and the budd co also calls for the firm to improve 
recordkeeping and to protect employees from excessive noise 
last december osha proposed 33 million in fines against the 
company for more than 840 alleged violations at its philadelphia 
plant including failure to tell some workers that tests showed 
their hearing was deteriorating 
government regulatory agencies frequently reduce proposed fines 
after negotiating with alleged violators 
budd which makes doors lift gates and other body stampings for 
motor vehicles has about 2400 people working at the philadelphia 
plant the troy michbased company is a subsidiary of the west 
germanys thyssen industries and has plants in indiana kentucky 
michigan ohio pennsylvania and tennessee 
under the settlement the company will monitor noise and test 
employees to identify all workers exposed above a certain noise 
level the workers will be notified of the results and trained to 
use hearing protectors the labor department said 
in addition the company has agreed to reduce noise at its 
philadelphia plant through engineering controls and repair and 
maintenance of equipment the company also will train employees to 
keep records in line with agency requirements 
