<TEXT>
here is a look at developments following elections held sunday 
in several countries 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
peru 
mario vargas llosa the acclaimed novelist once considered a 
sure bet to become perus next president finds himself sidetracked 
by the fujimori phenomenon 
agricultural engineer alberto fujimori 51 son of japanese 
immigrants and a political unknown until a month ago forced vargas 
llosa into a runoff and is now favored to win the presidency 
fujimori received 29 percent of the vote sunday to 339 percent 
for vargas llosa unofficial returns say vargas llosa needed a 
majority to avoid a runoff which now probably will take place in 
early june 
luis alva castro candidate of the governing leftofcenter 
aprista party received 164 percent two marxist candidates split 
11 percent of the vote and the rest was divided among four minor 
candidates and blank and void ballots 
public opinion analysts say fujimoris strong secondplace 
finish sunday reflected peruvians alienation from traditional 
political parties and their desire for miraculous painless 
solutions to perus ills 
inflation runs at more than 2000 percent annually more than 
18000 people have died in the struggle between radical shining 
path guerrillas and security forces 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
greece 
constantine mitsotakis leader of new democracy cut a deal with 
the small democratic renewal party to form a government after 
sunday election returns showed his conservative party one seat 
short of a parliamentary majority 
official results showed new democracy won 150 of the 300 seats 
in the singlehouse parliament in the third parliamentary elections 
in 10 months the conservatives also fell short in june and 
november elections 
mitsotakis met monday with costis stephanopoulos and they agreed 
democratic renewals one victorious candidate would support new 
democracy to give it 151 seats the government will be allnew 
democracy however 
the political impasse since last june has left untended the 
problems of a crumbling economy and growing urban terrorism 
with almost all of the 16584 polling stations reporting 
official returns gave new democracy 4689 percent of the vote the 
panhellenic socialist movement or pasok 3862 percent and 123 
seats the communistled coalition of the left and progress 1028 
percent and 19 seats and the eight remaining seats split among 
four independents two greekmoslems one environmentalist and 
democratic renewal 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
