leaders of the hungarian democratic forum the conservative 
party that won elections ending 43 years of communist rule in 
hungary began work monday to form a centerright governing 
coalition 
democratic forum won nearly 43 percent of the vote and 165 of 
the 386 house seats contested sunday and in a first round of 
elections two weeks ago unofficial results showed 
jozsef antall president of democratic forum told reporters 
monday we have the possibility of forming a solid government 
with our possible coalition partners the agrarian independent 
smallholders third with 11 percent of the vote and the christian 
democrats tied for fifth with more than 5 percent 
unofficial results gave the smallholders 43 seats and the 
christian democrats 21 
such a coalition would force the liberal league of free 
democrats and its ideological ally the league of young democrats 
into the opposition the former communists now grouped into the 
governing socialist party probably would join them 
the free democrats won about 24 percent of parliament with 92 
seats the young democrats were tied with the christian democrats 
for 21 seats and the socialist party was fourth with more than 8 
percent for 33 seats 
antalls new government is expected to introduce market forces 
into the economy 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
yugoslavia 
communist reformer milan kucan got the most votes for president 
of slovenia in yugoslavias first free election since 1945 but 
must face conservative rival joze pucnik in a runoff election 
results showed monday 
the runoff will be held april 22 because neither won a majority 
with 98 percent of the vote counted from sundays elections 
kucan led with 444 percent pucnik of demos a coalition of five 
conservative groups was second with 262 percent independent ivan 
kramberger third with 189 percent and marko demsar of the liberal 
party fourth with 105 percent 
an estimated 11 million slovenians 75 percent of those 
eligible voted in communist yugoslavias first multiparty election 
since world war ii they also chose a legislature from candidates 
representing 17 political parties 
political analysts predict a close contest in the runoff pucnik 
wants slovenia to secede from yugoslavia kucan advocates a more 
cautious approach 
initial results suggest the slovenian communist party its name 
newly changed to the party of democratic renewal will become the 
largest single party in the republics legislature but demos will 
have the most seats 
support for secession has grown in slovenia the most liberal 
and prosperous of yugoslavias six republics because of the slow 
pace of political and economic reform elsewhere in the federation 
