<TEXT>
a history of polands tumultuous 70s by 
former communist party leader edward gierek topped local bestseller 
lists as poles stood in blocklong lines monday to buy copies of 
his memoir 
the aborted decade is a 201page book that features a 
series of interviews of gierek by journalist janusz rolicki 
conducted from november to february 
despite its relatively high local price of 528 lines quickly 
formed to buy the book which was sold from the backs of trucks and 
sidewalk tables 
much of the interest appeared to stem from a desire for a 
behindthescenes look at the countrys recent political history 
despite his being deposed in 1980 the 77yearold gierek is 
remembered fondly by many poles for raising the standard of living 
by borrowing heavily from abroad the loans contributed in great 
part to polands 40 billion debt which it still is unable to pay 
the debt and subsequent economic problems led to the birth and 
rise of solidarity the first independent labor union in the soviet 
bloc gierek legalized solidarity in 1980 but because of the 
unions growing demands coupled with pressing economic problems he 
was forced to retire 
gierek first secretary of the party from 197080 is polands 
first communist ruler to return to the public eye after being 
ousted the ruling communists fell from power last year at the 
beginning of the east european reforms and in its wake the 
solidarityled government was created 
there was no chance to publish this before gierek admits in 
a postscript to the paperback issued by a private publisher fakt 
he says the communist party leadership during the 1980s rejected 
his repeated requests for an objective reassessment of the 1970s 
a nations forgetting or falsifying its past loses the proper 
perspective for coming years he wrote 
the history of peoples poland is not a history of a wild and 
festering struggle by society against the authorities first of all 
it is a history of the life of several generations full of bright 
and dark spots 
he also said he had been imprisoned and laughed at and later 
condemned to ignomity and humiliation without the right to 
defend himself 
gierek was briefly interned after martial law was declared in 
poland in 1981 the imprisonment was an effort by the countrys 
leaders to portray the crackdown as being aimed at both rebellious 
union leaders and corrupt party officials 
he had come to power as the first secretary of the polish united 
workers party in december 1970 succeeding wladyslaw gomulka who 
