<TEXT>
moscows opposition to lithuanian independence 
can be compared to abraham lincolns fight to keep the south from 
seceding a soviet official said monday 
yuri a reshetov head of the soviet foreign ministrys 
department for international humanitarian cooperation and human 
rights told a news conference he visited washingtons lincoln 
memorial on sunday 
the american civil war president in his second inaugural 
address in 1865 said that he is fighting against the forces which 
are seeking to dissolve the union abraham lincoln saved the 
american union reshetov said 
we have been together with lithuania with estonia and with 
latvia for many many years he said i still hope that what 
unites us is much stronger than what is capable of leading to 
dissolution of our union 
reshetov argued that lithuanias fate should be decided by a 
popular vote rather than by the march 11 declaration by the 
parliament in vilnius rejecting the 1940 soviet annexation 
stasys lozoraitis jr charge daffaires of the lithuanian 
legation in washington said at a separate news conference that 
since the western powers have never recognized the soviet 
annexation of lithuania the international law that should be 
applied is that the soviets should withdraw 
a majority of lithuanians are for independence lozoraitis said 
but a referendum would be a trap for neighboring estonia and 
latvia where sizable minorities oppose independence 
all three baltic republics were part of the russian empire from 
the late 18th century until after world war i they were 
independent between the wars but forcibly annexed by the soviet 
union in 1940 after moscow took control of the republics under 
terms of a secret pact with nazi germany 
the baltic republics have continued to maintain legations as 
their diplomatic representatives in washington 
reshetov said the soviet union supports selfdetermination but 
said selfdetermination can take various forms and the creation 
of a new state is the highest form 
in international law it is well established that the means of 
determining the right to selfdetermination is a referendum or 
plebiscite the foreign ministry official said 
asked about the presence of soviet troops in lithuania reshetov 
said the only thing that is happening in this respect in 
lithuania is that law and order should be upheld in this part of 
the soviet union 
lozoraitis however said we can maintain law and order by 
ourselves and dont need the red army to maintain law and order 
the soviet official was also asked about the expulsion of 
western correspondents from lithuania on april 1 and about the 
occupation of a newspaper plant in vilnius by soviet troops on 
march 31 
reshetov replied that the journalists were exluded under 
international law principles that also permit exclusion of foreign 
diplomats he said he hoped it will be just for a limited time 
the official also said that in recent months lithuanian 
newspapers that opposed secession received no newsprint from 
lithuanian factories but newspapers in favor of secession 
received plenty of paper 
lozoraitis denied that there was any policy of denying newsprint 
to papers that opposed independence he said some newspapers were 
not able to get paper because they lacked the financial means 
