<TEXT>
dr louis sullivan the us secretary of health 
said monday that the united states would end up with more addiction 
and more deaths if it ever legalized drugs 
legalization would be a tragic horrible mistake and its 
folly has become so apparent that no one should seriously offer it 
as an alternative he told a plenary session at a drug summit of 
112 nations 
sullivan said there was a very small but vocal minority in 
the united states that opposes the war on drugs 
we must beware of those who argue that ending substance abuse 
requires too much effort time and resources he said some of 
these critics claim that legalization is the answer but as we 
have discovered in the united states it is no answer at all 
despite the us investment of significant resources in drug 
prevention during the 1960s and 1970s he said those two decades 
encouraged pseudolegalization and social tolerance 
in the united states our experience with those two decades 
demonstrated the price we will pay for appeasement more drugs 
more addiction and more death sullivan said 
legalization would remove the stigma from drug use the 
pressure for treatment and the few restraints there are on cost and 
supply he said 
legalization would send the people the message that our 
society is morally indifferent to their use of harmful drugs he 
said 
british prime minister margaret thatcher opening the threeday 
conference also urged delegates to make it absolutely clear that 
you cant beat drugtaking by legalizing drugs 
that is the way to destroy young lives ruin families and 
undermine society itself our task is to protect young people not 
deliberately expose them to danger she said 
i can assure you that our government will never legalize 
illicit drugs hard or soft the prime minister said 
