<TEXT>
trombonist louis nelson the last member of 
the original preservation hall bands went to his grave in style 
monday in a traditional jazz funeral echoing through the narrow 
streets of old new orleans 
nelson 87 died thursday 10 days after a hitandrun car 
accident 
he was really the last of the old crop of trombonists said 
harold dejan leader of the olympia brass band which led the 
funeral procession there are plenty of imitators but he was the 
last of the good old crop 
the olympia normally a dozen or so musicians was joined by 
about two dozen others for the funeral among them were visitors 
from australia switzerland and los angeles butch thompson 
nelsons pianist on his last tours to japan came from st paul 
with cornetist charley devore 
about 500 people gathered outside the funeral home and followed 
the band as it walked the edge of the french quarter playing old 
hymns like sweet bye and bye what a friend and precious 
lord take me home 
the entourage turned on bourbon street and wound through 
