navy band 
when the tempo lifted for an upbeat version of closer walk 
umbrellas the traditional ornament of a second line that joyous 
street dance after the funeral popped open and the mourners 
started clapping in rhythm 
then abruptly an unexpected shift to a waltz it was after 
the ball one of nelsons favorites a couple of lilting courses 
later the band drew away the bouncing shouting crowd with a 
raucous saints go marching in 
the cortege left by the crowd and the body cut loose from 
earthly friends made its way to the cemetery too far away for the 
crowd to walk 
nelson played many such funerals with many of these musicians 
he worked with dejan when the olympia cut its first album of parade 
music in 1956 
nelson preferred the oldtime sweet music with a sliding 
melodic trombone influenced by the swing era but he could also 
play the rough tailgate style as he did with the kid thomas 
valentine band 
he was with kid thomas when russell first recorded them in 1949 
he and thomas were still together in 1961 when they were one of the 
bands that opened preservation hall dedicated to keeping 
traditional new orleans music alive 
since then nelson played with many bands including george 
lewis kid howard and billie and dede pierce and became an 
international star making periodic tours of europe south america 
and japan 
at the time of his death he was playing two nights a week at 
preservation hall and was leading the louis nelson all stars which 
was booked for a summer tour of japan it would have been his tenth 
to that country 
his last performance was the saturday before his car was hit by 
a woman who ran a red light 
the last night he played he sounded as good as ever said 
jazz historian bill russell 
