<TEXT>
a summary of developments in the news industry for april 29 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the nations press is too comfortable too 
wellpaid too much part of the establishment for the countrys own 
good the president of the american society of newspaper editors 
told colleagues april 4 
we often think of ourselves as davids fighting the 
establishment but the public sees us more and more as statusquo 
establishment goliaths said loren ghiglione publisher and 
editor of the news of southbridge mass 
he cited a poll showing most people think that news media are 
under the influence of powerful people and organizations 
ghiglione addressing the societys 67th annual meeting 
proposed that editors each adopt an institution that makes us 
uncomfortable a prison a mental institution a noisy 
overcrowded bigcity school an aids hospital ward and try to 
work in that world or at least understand it 
he told of his own experiences removing his glasses his belt 
his watch and his shoes as he was admitted to a number of prisons 
in the past year while taking part in an asne study of prison 
journalism each time he said he vowed not to do it again but 
in an era of lawandorder electricchair politics i know i 
should go back 
while we say we comfort the afflicted and afflict the 
comfortable we need to guard against looking at the world 
increasingly through the eyes of the comfortable ghiglione said 
arguing that newspapermen have lost touch with their readers 
one poll showed that half of newspaper journalists earn over 
40000 a year but only 18 percent of the public does he said 
and many of us live in almost exclusively white middleclass 
worlds and send our children to private or suburban public 
schools 
he argued that the world needs editors who will fight 
another speaker author and prizewinning reporter david 
halberstam told the editors that the demands by owners of 
newspapers and newspaper company stocks for everrising profits are 
putting newspapers in jeopardy 
theres a question of how much water you can bring out of the 
stone halberstam said at what point are you taking out more 
than youre putting in 
i think the threat to us is not from the outside not from the 
government not from television it is from ourselves 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in the first survey of its kind homosexual 
members of the staffs of american newspapers said their papers do a 
poor job with news about gays or of concern to them 
the gay journalists said their papers treat them fairly and give 
them opportunities to advance but rarely call on their insights 
into gay lifestyles in the same way black reporters are asked to 
help guide coverage of black issues 
and some newsrooms harbor a palpable undercurrent of bias a 
summary of the findings concludes one respondent commented that 
her colleagues who make snide homophobic comments and jokes are 
the same people who write those sensitive stories and 
editorials 
the survey was made public april 4 at the annual meeting of the 
american society of newspaper editors it was undertaken at the 
request of outgoing asne president loren ghiglione who asked 
whether antigay discrimination infects todays newsrooms 
when word of the survey circulated 205 homosexual members of 
the staffs of us newspapers volunteered to respond threefifths 
said they were openly gay and twothirds signed their 
questionnaires 
ninetytwo percent said they knew other people on the staff who 
were gay and the majority of them estimated that fewer than 20 
percent of the homosexuals on their papers were openly gay 
many experts estimate that one american in 10 is gay 
why does it matter asked leroy f aarons an executive of 
the tribune of oakland calif who coordinated the project he 
said the subject is important because more than ever before 
editors are grappling with a swirl of social and political currents 
around alternative lifestyle issues 
domestic partners legislation gay adoption 
antidiscrimination laws fundamentalist attacks on the gay 
lifestyle morality and public responsibility and of course the 
stillraging aids epidemic have brought onceeasily ignored issues 
into demanding focus he said 
the respondents gave especially low ratings to the way their 
papers treated gay lifestyles community events and politics and 
only slightly better ratings to treatment of violence against gays 
civil rights issues and legislation 
as for terminology nearly a third said they found the term 
homosexual to be prejudiced explaining that it refers narrowly 
to sex whereas the term gay refers to lifestyles or issues 
aarons ended his report to the editors by publicly revealing his 
own sexual orientation 
i a paragraph scribbled at the end of his typewritten text and 
read hurriedly in a choked voice he said 
i want you to know that the doing of this report has had 
tremendous impact on gay and lesbian journalists across the nation 
it has given them hope and new optimism it has enhanced their 
respect for this organization i as an editor and a gay man am 
proud of asne 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the us court of appeals says it agrees with 
a lower court that the seven bell operating companies cannot enter 
the longdistance or telephone equipment businesses 
but the april 3 ruling reopens the possibility that the 
socalled baby bells can sell electronic information services to 
homes and offices a prospect opposed by newspaper groups 
the decision means that us district judge harold greene must 
consider anew whether the bell companies may be allowed to develop 
socalled electronic yellow pages allowing consumers to shop 
and bank among other possibilities via cheap easytouse video 
terminals 
a prototype governmentoperated system in france called minitel 
already serves 5 million homes and offices and offers 8000 
different services 
the threejudge appeals panel found that greene ruled correctly 
when in his 1987 triennial review of the american telephone amp 
telegraph co antitrust settlement he sustained the original order 
barring the seven spinoff companies from competing with their 
onetime parent in the longdistance and telephone manufacturing 
arenas 
but appeals judges abner mikva harry edwards and laurence 
silberman faulted greenes legal reasoning when as part of that 
same review he only partly opened the door for the operating 
companies to expand into computerbased information services 
greene allowed the bell companies to offer computer gateways and 
access menus for databases and services offered by other companies 
but not to generate those services themselves that precluded 
them from pursuing a us version of minitel 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

