<TEXT>
there was a time when the british band 
marillion performed poetic tales of midlife crisis tragic love 
affairs politics and alcoholism that bordered on the negative 
but these days with a new optimism and a new lead singer the 
group sings of strife in northern ireland in the elegant track 
easter of love gone obsessive in the uninvited guest and 
of global warming in the title track of seasons end their new 
lp 
im trying to deal with all of those things on a soul level 
on a humanity level rather than trying to make some kind of 
political point said steve hogarth who replaced the 
introspective derek dick who was called fish as vocalist and 
lyricist 
i think its a great romantic notion to turn all the poets 
into politicians he said i dont think its our place or 
musicians place to stand up and propose solutions other than to 
propose hope and to propose the wider and more common sense things 
like love and peace 
that attitude carries over in marillions live performances 
hogarth is engaging on stage leaping on to speaker cabinets to 
sing and making frequent eye contact with his audience 
i try to be a bit friendly he said i try and love them 
i know that sounds like an insincere american sort of thing to say 
but i do try in all sincerity to love them while im singing to 
them i think that youve got to put something out to people to get 
something back from them that is genuine 
though popular in england for about a decade marillion is just 
beginning to gain an audience in the united states 
the group started in 1978 as silmarillion a name taken from the 
jrr tolkein novel their leader was the enigmatic fish others 
in the band were guitarist steve rothery bassist pete trewavas 
keyboardist mark kelly and drummer ian mosley 
they released their first album script for a jesters tear 
in 1983 under their new name marillion 
through 1988 marillion released six albums their most notable 
efforts with fish were the brilliant concept works misplaced 
childhood released in 1985 and clutching at straws in 1987 
fish left the band in 1988 and was replaced in 1989 by hogarth 
who had been in several lesser bands around britain fish has just 
released a solo album vigil in a wilderness of mirrors which 
is already in the top 10 in britain 
hogarth was familiar with the bands material before he joined 
but didnt know the group was looking for a new singer until his 
publisher told him 
id never seen the band play and i wasnt a member of the fan 
club or anything so i didnt understand the band in terms of how 
they actually are as people hogarth said in a telephone 
interview following a concert stop in philadelphia 
but the connection between hogarth and the rest of marillion was 
immediate 
they all knew straight off that it was right they dont know 
why i think they just got the feeling that i was coming from the 
same planet in terms of what stimulated me hogarth said 
the band had been looking for someone whos just going to be 
himself he said and they were more than willing to use music he 
had written 
i think thats why spiritually the band feels so new 
hogarth said because it has been a natural process we havent 
taken anything that was old and tried to chisel away at whats new 
in order to make it fit 
however fishs departure was a strain on both sides hogarth 
said 
the band were beginning to have a problem with the stuff fish 
was writing as well as fish was beginning to have a problem with 
wanting to work with the band hogarth said 
the problem the band were having with his writing was that he 
was beginning to be so introverted that the band were beginning to 
worry that nobody else in the world was ever going to relate to 
what he was going on about 
hogarth said it was a happier band that recorded seasons end 
we had a great time writing the album and then a great time 
recording it because we coproduced it hogarth said we didnt 
have anyone telling us what to do when we were recording the album 
so the spirit right from day one has been extremely positive and i 
think its reflected not only in the album but in the spirit on 
stage and the live shows as well 
hogarth thinks the band can make it in the united states but 
will have to do it through touring because nobodys ever go records to 
death on daytime rading to 
play ourio thats not the kind of 
band we are and in a way thats our strength 
but in a way the singer appreciates the bands anonymity 
were in the fortunate position that our record company hasnt 
the foggiest idea why our fans love it and so they leave us to 
just get on with it he said 
</TEXT>
