<TEXT>
an old maxim that it is stocks rather than the 
stock market that should matter to individual investors is getting 
a workout on wall street these days it is written in the averages 
in the years first quarter the dow jones industrial average 
made up of very large and mostly very bluechip companies slipped 
only 50 points or so which works out to a drop of 17 percent 
the standard amp poors 500stock average which includes a good 
many relatively smaller companies fell more sharply about 38 
percent or more than double the descent rate of the dj average 
the even broader value line composite index whose 1700 members 
include an even bigger mix of smaller companies fell 58 percent 
leaving it about 15 percent lower than in the summer of 1987 
the verdict many stocks especially smaller stocks are down a 
great deal more than is indicated by the dj average without 
question the most widely used numerical indicator of market 
strength 
smaller stocks have been hit hard for several years now wright 
investors service points out that in 23 of the past 27 quarters 
small stocks have lagged behind the bigger brandname companies 
that dominate most indicators 
it is a rare situation and one that tends to confuse a lot of 
people and even some analysts 
has the stock market for example already had its correction 
disquised from popular view by a rather slight decline in the dj 
average is the correction yet to come is the direction of the 
market up or down 
the confusion might be greatest of course for those who judge 
the market by the averages instead of the prices of individual 
stocks or groups of stocks because the current market is an 
unusual mix 
utility stocks which had risen sharply late in 1989 were big 
losers in the first quarter of this year falling 68 percent 
financial stocks fell more than 7 percent in both the final quarter 
of 1989 and the first of 1990 
in fact only four of 25 industry groups advanced in the first 
quarter and three of them construction metal production and 
electronics showed gains not so much because of strength but 
because they had fallen earlier 
such figures drive home the point made by so many investment 
advisers that popular averages hardly tell the full story or even 
a realistic one that people invest in individual stocks rather 
than in the market and that they must watch stock prices rather 
than stock market averages 
todays stock market also recalls a kernel of advice underlying 
a good many conservative investment philosophies that within any 
industry even those performing poorly you may find companies that 
defy the generality 
the lesson it seems is that the forest isnt just a mass of 
trees but an assembly of individual trees and the stock market 
isnt a unit in itself but one made up of thousands of separate 
companies each distinct in its own way 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

