<TEXT>
a landmark agreement banning world ivory trade 
has begun to crumble posing a renewed threat to the survival of 
the african elephant conservationists say 
the opposition of several african nations had been expected but 
the bombshell came in january when great britain pulled out of the 
accord 
it was a shock to all conservationists says ginette hemley 
director of the us office of traffic the wildlife trade 
monitoring program of the world wildlife fund it was a massive 
turnaround on the part of the united kingdom 
britain had argued forcibly in favor of the ban last fall 
it came down to a fight between the british foreign minister 
and the environment minister hemley says the foreign minister 
recommended that britain pull out to ensure confidence in the hong 
kong economy she says 
the problem with that is it will keep open ivory markets that 
otherwise would have shut down says david western an ecologist 
in nairobi with wildlife conservation international and it sends 
out a signal to certain poachers in africa that hong kong is still 
good as a market and it therefore stimulates poaching once again 
in africa 
nevertheless the ivory trade ban coupled with decisions by the 
united states europe and japan to ban all ivory imports seems to 
have temporarily slowed the slaughter of african elephants hemley 
says 
right now were in a bit of a holding pattern she says 
while poaching is going on we have every reason to believe its 
slowed down dramatically the closing of the us and the european 
markets had a major major effect on the trade and hopefully on 
poaching in the field 
a study is under way to determine the bans precise effect on 
poaching she says 
compared with this time last year the poaching levels are 
down in kenya down in tanzania and down in zaire way down 
says western so viewed overall the picture looks more 
promising 
the price of luxury ivory products has dropped by 70 percent in 
the united states as demand has fallen says hemley in kenya the 
price paid to poachers has dropped from 20 to 50 per kilogram 
22 pounds to 2 to 5 per kilogram hemley says the average 
weight of a tusk in trade is 2 to 4 kilograms 
the population of african elephants has declined from 13 
million in 1979 to an estimated 625000 according to a report 
published in october by the ivory trade review group an 
international team of biologists and environmentalists 
highly organized poachers armed with automatic weapons roam 
freely across african borders killing 10 percent of the remaining 
elephants each year the report estimated 
at that rate elephants will be extinct in the wild within 30 
years says western one of the reports authors 
the report was prepared in advance of a meeting last october in 
lausanne switzerland of the international agency that regulates 
ivory trade 
at that meeting the convention on international trade in 
endangered species of wild fauna and flora delegates from more 
than 100 nations voted to ban trade in ivory around the world but 
with a lastminute compromise that threatened to undo the agreement 
countries were given 90 days to lodge reservations about 
their participation in the trade ban delegates also agreed to 
commission a special review of the ivory trade before the next 
cites meeting in 1992 where the ban conceivably could be 
overturned although that is not considered likely 
zimbabwe zambia south africa malawi and botswana filed 
reservations arguing that they are able to manage their herds well 
enough to cull ivory without depleting their elephant populations 
china also filed a reservation raising fears that a new market 
could develop there but western discounts that possibility 
china is in no position to buy up lots of ivory because it 
doesnt have the hard currency he says 
ivory carvers from hong kong reportedly also have begun moving 
to south korea which is not part of cites but the effect of that 
move also is uncertain 
south korea doesnt have the tradition of using ivory for 
trinkets and bangles and that market doesnt build up overnight 
says western 
hemley notes that south koreas role in wildlife trade has 
increased dramatically during the last few years 
it is a booming economy and potentially the biggest new market 
for luxury ivory products she says 
western who expressed concern last fall that an ironclad ivory 
ban hadnt been enacted is now more sanguine about the african 
elephants future 
the most important consumer countries japan europe and 
america will stick with the ban he says over 80 percent of 
the total demand is in those three countries 
hong kong where most of the worlds ivory carvers are located 
has a supply of 670 tons of ivory on hand reports indicate and 
may be stuck with it 
the hong kong traders are not going to have a very easy time 
unloading that consignment western says the shift in public 
opinion has been so great that ivory will not be a commodity you 
can wear any more elephants will be under much much less pressure 
in the next few yeits sort of touchandgo says hemley the fight 
is by no 
means over 
