<TEXT>
washington secretary of state jim baker is the scion of one of 
houstons most distinguished families the bakers of baker amp 
botts one of the largest and oldest law firms west of the 
mississippi 
his buttondown shirts say jab iii but he is actually the 
fourth james a baker 
the first his greatgrandfather was a civil war veteran and 
district judge who moved to houston and cofounded the firm after 
the war his grandfather known as captain baker a title bestowed 
by the ceremonial houston light guard was a founder and chairman 
of the texas commerce bank and most dramatically unraveled the 
murder of his client new york industrialist william march rice in 
the fall of 1900 captain baker proved that rice had been done in 
by a butler and lawyer who had prepared a false will his sleuthing 
saved the fortune with which rice university was built 
jim bakers father the third senior partner in baker amp botts 
was called the warden by jims friends he was a stern 
disciplinarian quick to administer whippings and urge jim and 
sister bonnie to new challenges like jumping off the high dive no 
matter how scared they were baker recalls his father often 
awakened him by throwing ice water into his face gets you up 
real fast he said 
following his father baker attended the hill school and 
princeton he did a twoyear stint in the marines commissioned as 
a lieutenant the korean war was on but he spent most of his time 
on a ship in the mediterranean then he went home to texas for law 
school where he made the law review and missed by one slot the 
order of the coif accorded the 10 percent of the graduating 
class he remains disappointed about that minor failure even 
dwells on it to this day 
baker barred from joining his fathers firm by a 
sinceabandoned antinepotism rule made his own mark as a 
corporate attorney amassing assets now estimated at 4 million 
he was little known outside legal circles and the houston 
country club where he and a fellow member won the tennis doubles 
championship twice in the early 1960s but baker a democrat by 
family tradition and george bush a local oilman and son of a 
connecticut republican senator kept politics out of their game 
</TEXT>
