of the joint center for urban studies at harvard universitys 
kennedy school of government 
detroit is actually leading a path that other cities may be on 
in the next 10 years brown says all communities are going to 
find that there isnt the central city housing demand that there 
has been 
even in the 70s when it was alleged that there was a 
backtothecity movement young people were more likely to be 
moving to the suburbs 
in detroit berg says the city and nine banks recently pooled 
40 million to form the detroit neighborhood investment corp 
which provides lowinterest loans for renovating existing housing 
a few private investors have joined the reclamation effort on 
their own 
a corporation headed by grosse pointe developer jim saros bought 
the 62yearold chalfonte apartments on the lower east side for 
400000 it spent an additional 700000 to renovate the 20unit 
building that had been vacant for seven years 
detroit has spent 15 million to demolish 3000 vacant 
structures this fiscal year the budget includes another 15 
million to tear down 3000 more buildings by june 30 
one of the things youre doing when you knock down the 
abandoned houses is do it quickly before it spreads like a 
cancer berg says 
marcell mayberry has seen that cancer ravage much of her lower 
eastside neighborhood now she fears it may reach algonquin 
street too 
a sagging woodframe bungalow next to mayberrys house is so 
far the only abandoned house on algonquin mayberry cuts the grass 
and joins other neighbors in keeping watch for arsonists or 
vandals she says she never sees the owner 
the neighborhoods decline began about 10 years ago when 
absentee landlords began renting to welfare clients and neglected 
their property mayberry says later came the crack dealers 
burglars and arsonists 
mayberry is unimpressed by grayhaven a condominiummarina 
project under construction near her home 
when this crack cocaine came in thats when things started 
disappearing she says its an epidemic and there aint 
nothing anyone can do about it if theyve got the same problems 
weve got how are grayhaven residents going to help 
in cleveland 16 million has been spent to demolish abandoned 
buildings over the past decade says mike marcelino a spokesman 
for mayor michael white that compares with 15 million this year 
alone in detroit whose population is about twice that of cleveland 
when you start tearing down housing you can quickly ruin a 
street or neighborhood marcelino says hows it going to 
affect the houses on either side a lot of people cannot afford a 
new house 
cleveland officials have created a land bank to pool vacant 
property in hopes of redevelopment says norman krumholtz the 
citys former planning director 
in strategic locations they assemble enough property so you 
have some kind of reasonable development says krumholtz a 
