<TEXT>
its one of the last of the mom and pop 
jails a place where serving time is a family affair if youve got 
to be locked up the gilmer county jail in west virginia would sure 
beat rikers island in new york city 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
at lee and terri fredericks place room 
guests enjoy oldfashioned home cooking and are greeted at 
breakfast with a friendly good morning 
they can watch television play table tennis in the recreation 
room use the telephone and entertain visitors in the familys 
garage 
but dont pack your bags for a weekend in the mountains the 
fredericks place is the gilmer county jail one of the nations 
last mom and pop jails 
the jail owes more to mayberry than to attica or alcatraz 
while inmates eat terris pasta pizza and meat dishes in their 
upstairs cells the fredericks are eating the same fare downstairs 
i just make extra for the guys upstairs mrs frederick says 
every other thursday the couple pulls their 1986 chrysler out 
of their garage and sets up folding chairs so inmates can entertain 
visitors 
the fredericks house rules are posted in the jails recreation 
room 
golden rules if you open it close it if you take it out 
lock it up if it will brighten someones day say it 
the fredericks live with their two sons joey 6 and lynn 2 
in a threebedroom brick house whose upstairs cells have housed the 
countys criminals for 50 years 
the twostory building built of fleshcolored brick sits atop 
a hill sandwiched between the county courthouse and a glenville 
state college dormitory 
the rest of the neighborhood is made up of modest singlefamily 
homes that look a lot like the frederick house except for the bars 
on the windows 
lee 29 is a former truck driver who took the job of jailer a 
year ago terri 27 who lived in the house as a child when her 
parents ran the jail now does the cooking and cleaning 
in her spare time she dispatches sheriffs deputies local 
police ambulances and rescue workers from her living room the 
room also has alarms for glenvilles two banks 
until recently when a night jailer was hired one of them was 
always on duty from 7 am to midnight after that prisoners could 
summon lee by pushing a button on the elevator that connects the 
first and second floors 
mrs frederick stays in touch with wallmounted loudspeakers 
that allow her to hear calls when shes working in the kitchen 
its easy to know whats happening in the jail because we can 
hear them right through the ceiling mrs frederick says 
frederick says his sons are not allowed upstairs no matter how 
curious they get 
theyll find out about this stuff soon enough anyway he 
says 
on an average day the jail houses about nine prisoners most 
detained for drunken driving destruction of property or game law 
violations 
in the evenings prisoners play table tennis or watch television 
in a family sized recreation room they have access to the couples 
telephone every night but long distance calls are not allowed 
such homey touches arent lost on the inmates 
lee treats me ok and the foods all right but i just dont 
like being in jail says carson yeager 45 who described himself 
as a chronic alcoholic 
yeager is one of the fredericks regulars 
the majority of ours are not hardened criminals frederick 
says they dont need to be exposed to that type of people 
some former inmates even come back to say hello occasionally a 
21yearold former inmate now incarcerated elsewhere has written 
the couple four letters in the last two months 
still rural mom and pop jails are increasingly being phased 
out because of generally substandard conditions high maintenance 
costs and a move toward regional jails 
they are a rapidly dying breed says michael otoole chief 
of the jails division of the national institute of corrections 
more than 19 million people filter through 3300 county jails 
each year according to us justice department statistics 
small jails are not cost effective otoole says although 
a lot are wellmeaning and wellintentioned the conditions of 
confinement arent what they should be a lot are just incapable of 
being up to standards 
the operation rises and falls on the integrity of the 
operator for each example where somebody is fulfilling their 
responsibility you can look at another side of the ledger and see 
someone who shouldnt have any authority over anybody in custody 
whatsoever 
recently the state facilities review panel took aim at the 
fredericks warning it would shut the jail down if gilmer county 
officials didnt add staff at the jail 
so sheriff kenneth smith jr hired a nightshift jailer and 
beefed up the parttime staff so the fredericks only have to work 
40 hours a week 
its cramped our personal lives a little bit sure 
frederick says 
