that they can create a black leader theyre going to only be 
modestly successful 
williams 57 was born in memphis tenn the only child of ed 
williams a onearmed jazz piano player and his wife georgia a 
maid at hotels and welltodo private homes in the city 
from her williams learned the value of finding and assembling 
seemingly evasive information 
williams says his mother would often bring home books clothes 
and other artifacts from the homes in which she worked 
this is what that white boys reading now you ought to be 
reading it williams recalls her saying he says he read the 
materials that were otherwise not available to black children in 
the segregated school systems of the south during the 1930s and 
1940s 
bebe bowers fingall a high school english teacher called 
mama by her students helped hone williams competitive spirit 
and selfconfidence 
williams says that as one of mamas pets he was drawn 
toward all kinds of writing and speaking anthologies and plays 
after earning a bachelors degree in journalism from the 
university of illinois he did graduate work in political science 
at atlanta and howard universities 
williams also served as director of the center for policy 
studies at the university of chicago he was director of the us 
office of equal employment opportunity and a foreign service 
reserve officer at the state department 
williams has two children a son edward 24 who is a graduate 
student at the peabody school of music at johns hopkins university 
and a daughter tracy 26 who is an actress at the living stage 
theater in washington dc 
his 21yearold stepson terrence reddick is a senior at george 
mason university in virginia 
but his baby is the joint center for political studies as 
reflected on the wall of his office in a framed and matted 
paraphrase of a popular slogan have you hugged your 501 c 3 
today a reference to the section in us law that grants 
taxexempt status to nonprofit organizations 
the center is funded by 3 million a year in grants from private 
foundations and corporations 
what he has done is to provide a place for substantial high 
quality objective research where none existed before says 
norman ornstein of the american enterprise institute a 
conservative washington think tank 
rep augustus hawkins dcalif the oldest and longestserving 
black member of the house and chairman of the education and labor 
committee says he calls on the centers statistical data and 
analysis on a variety of issues if i want to focus in on a 
minority viewpoint or get the specifics 
the unofficial link between black elected officials and center 
dates to its beginning when noted black psychologist kenneth clark 
and several of the countrys thenleading black politicians founded 
the center and secured a 2 million grant from the ford foundation 
williams hopes to secure the centers financial future with a 
10 million endowment the ford foundation has pledged 5 million 
which williams is working to match 
the center which celebrated its 20th anniversary this month 
opened its doors in 1970 to provide technical assistance to a newly 
emerging cadre of black elected officials from the ranks of 
teachers preachers farmers and local community activists 
our role was to help them better understand the processes of 
governance to share some information and some expertise about 
administration planning budgeting identification of resource 
acquisition those kinds of technical things williams says 
the center also served to document the nature and extent of 
black political participation he says 
</TEXT>
