<TEXT>
 
pale columbia toad the wet sprocket 
 
toad the wet sprockets new album pale exemplifies 
everything thats wrong about the wheezing alternative rock scene 
far from the cutting edge the underground scene has too many 
imitators instead of innovators the reigning gods are still 
rem which methodically built a successful career with 
originality and relentless work 
since the early 1980s rem has had more impersonators than 
the late elvis presley toad the wet sprocket is only the latest to 
emulate the form rather than the substance of rem 
pale is loaded with moody slightly incongruous lyrics the 
guitar rock mixes the jangle and the drone the covers a grainy 
picture of something indistinguishable and the band photo is blurry 
sound familiar 
admittedly the failure of an entire genre is a tough burden to 
place on the shoulders of an unassuming california rock band 
theyre somewhat adept interpreters the sound is more muscular 
than murmurera rem though the songs of course lack 
distinctiveness 
but it would be far better to see bands try to make their mark 
with their own visions rather than someone elses 
by david bauder associated press writer 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
chamber orchestra conducted by jahja ling 
 
rolf smedvig has recorded frequently as a member of the 
superlative empire brass quintet and played six years with the 
boston symphony joining the orchestra at the remarkable age of 19 
surprisingly this is his first solo endeavor on disc its a 
good one his playing has life and spirit and smedvig knows how to 
scale his performance up or down for the work at hand he also has 
a wonderful mellow tone that can even fool the listener into 
hearing an oboe 
aside from the haydn eflat concerto he doesnt have much 
topquality raw material with which to work but then all trumpet 
soloists have to deal with a narrow field 
another work on the program is the eflat concerto by johann 
nepomuk hummel one of historys corrections that is he was 
tremendously popular and highly regarded in his day but has since 
fallen into a deserved obscurity 
his concerto is secondrate and uninteresting yet a staple of 
the instrument nevertheless smedvig calls attention to the 
pleasing moments in this work 
he also displays some beautiful legato playing in the haydn 
andante ling and the scottish players make an excellent 
contribution in this piece and are firstrate in general 
also on the program is a routine baroque concerto by giuseppe 
torelli a nicely tossedoff piece of fluff by a young vincenzo 
bellini originally written for oboe and a transcription of a 
violin concerto by giuseppe tartini 
the last work has a striking andante movement with lovely 
bittersweet melodies it seems destined for plunder by a wine 
advertiser looking for a bucolic soundtrack 
by daniel wakin associated press writer 
