<TEXT>
opec member nations produced an estimated 
2409 million barrels a day of crude oil in march the highest 
monthly output since 1981 the weekly middle east economic survey 
reported monday 
the influential newsletter said the production was up from 2362 
million barrels per day in february and 2332 million in january 
daily production in december was only slightly lower at 24 million 
the newsletter said iran showed the biggest increase in 
production jumping from 28 million barrels a day in february to 
315 million in march 
it is the first time since august that iran has been able to 
produce at the level of its 314 million barrels per day quota 
assigned under the cartels shared production system 
observers will be interested to see whether their level can be 
sustained in the coming months the newsletter said export 
facilities were severely damaged during the 198088 war with iraq 
but the government made repairs its first priority 
the overall production level was well above the ceiling of 221 
million barrels per day that the organization of petroleum 
exporting countries agreed on for production in the first six 
months of 1990 some members led by the united arab emirates and 
kuwait have been ignoring their production quotas and calling for 
their abolition 
last week the parisbased international energy agency estimated 
march production at 237 million barrels a day 
oil prices soared in january but have been gradually slipping 
since falling in early march below the cartels target of 18 a 
barrel to about 1775 for the average of a basket of seven crude 
oils 
the newsletter said the supply and demand for opec crude are 
roughly in balance 
