<TEXT>
the gears grind the engine growls and the 
rig jumps a curb bumps into a shiny corvette and rolls over a stop 
sign 
at the hands of an untrained driver a 45foot trailer truck can 
do a lot of damage but in what doron precision systems inc says 
is the worlds first affordable truck driver training simulator 
all the damage is to the ego 
the truck and the corvette weigh only a few pounds and the 
scene out the windows is a fourscreen live tv show 
step on the gas you cant hurt a thing said doron 
president carl wenzinger as a firsttime truck driver took the 
wheel checked his mirrors let out the clutch and attempted to 
back up to a dock at the end of a narrow alley 
doron is the company that builds those futuristic capsules that 
rock and roll a dozen shopping mall patrons at a time through a 
filmed roller coaster adventure a san francisco cable car ride or 
a helicopter flight over manhattan 
but wenzinger said his first and still most important business 
is creating realistic training devices for car bus and truck 
drivers the binghamton ny company claims to be the world 
leader in audiovisual driver training equipment 
this is not a video game wenzinger said we are in the 
serious business of traffic safety 
the company is keeping parts of its new l300 vehicle 
maneuvering trainer system secret behind black plastic sheets 
during public showings until all of the patents are accepted 
but what was uncovered in a demonstration last week was a 
lifesized cab complete with steering wheel and most of the gauges 
and controls of a normal truck two video projectors for a sweeping 
view of the road and two 24inch television sets for side windows 
with inset rearview mirrors 
wenzinger also acknowledged what was not immediately obvious 
until the silver corvette at the side of the road bounced rather 
than crunched the l300s driver is actually controlling a scale 
model which can either be placed in another room or stacked on top 
of the cab the scene includes a cab and trailer mounted with 
miniature video cameras 
it doesnt make sense to tie up an instructor fulltime in the 
front seat wenzinger said 
the whole thing could fit into a large living room the cost 
about 130000 compared to several million dollars for airplane or 
railroad simulators that use computergenerated images 
the difference in conducting training in an l300 and a real 
truck wenzinger said is that the trainee burns no fuel cant 
destroy the transmission doesnt wear out the tires or brakes and 
cant damage the training course 
it also saves on instructors he said one can monitor several 
simulators at a time 
the disadvantage is that the machine cant simulate highway 
driving the model would have to be too big some of the training 
still has to be in a classroom simulator with a movie screen or in 
a real rig 
the first two l300 simulators are to be delivered late this 
month to the pinellas technical education center run by pinellas 
county fla 
i think its fantastic said warren laux principal of the 
schools st petersburg campus 
i felt a lot of anxiety in driving it and didnt want people 
watching me said laux after testdriving the l300 id rather 
have students get those feelings in a simlulator than in a 100000 
piece of equipment they could ruin 
models could be constructed to duplicate most conditions a 
driver might face in turning parking or docking said david 
lindsey director of truck fleet operations for doron 
lindsey said courses could simulate rugged terrain for training 
in military vehicles or a school yard or city street for busdriver 
training 
