formal talks have broken off between two rival 
groups promoting different versions of atampts unix computer 
software though the groups said they have agreed to certain 
standards 
however the groups said they determined that a merger of the 
rivals could not be practically achieved at this time 
one of the groups unix international was set up by american 
telephone amp telegraph co the other the open software foundation 
was established by such atampt rivals as international business 
machines corp digital equipment corp and siemens ag of west 
germany 
the groups are vying for control of the unix operating system a 
base layer of software that fast is becoming an industry standard 
but different versions of unix have sprung up since atampt invented 
it meaning computers running on one version are not compatible 
with those running on another 
the open software foundation was established by the atampt rivals 
in 1988 when they became concerned that the phone giant was trying 
to retain control of unix rather than allow it to become an 
industry standard 
in response atampt formed unix international and ceded control of 
its versions of unix to the group 
the two groups said in november they were involved in formal 
discusssions on cooperation aimed at ending the perception they 
were rivals 
today they said the talks had concluded but that informal 
discussions would continue among the progress the groups cited 
were agreements to adhere to a number of industry standards 
