<DOCNO> AP900409-0225 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the planned union between west and 
east germany should prevent a west germany economic slowdown over 
the next two years experts said monday but they reiterated 
concerns that east german unemployment could soar 
west germanys five leading economic research institutes said 
increased demand resulting from the economic reconstruction of east 
germany likely will prevent a significant slowdown in west german 
growth 
klauswerner schatz an economist at the institute for world 
economics in kiel said the five institutes expect growth to slow 
marginally to 375 percent in 1990 from 4 percent in 1989 in 1991 
they expect the economy to grow at an almost similar pace 
in 1991 growth should be 15 percentage points higher than it 
would have been without economic union said schatz 
west germany has launched plans to create an economic union with 
east germany on the road to german unification under such a union 
west germany virtually would control east germanys economy as it 
rebuilds its eastern neighbor 
monetary union in which west germanys strong mark will replace 
east germanys nearly worthless currency is a central part of 
plans for economic union 
some west germans have raised concerns that unification could 
prove to be a heavy economic burden 
west german foreign minister hansdietrich genscher said monday 
part of the costs of unification could be covered by spending less 
on defense some opposition politicians have said west germany will 
have to raise taxes to cover the high price for unity 
but the five institutes said west german growth likely would 
handle unification costs 
in the midterm tax increases will not be necessary 
schatz said 
but schatz also called on west german and east german 
politicians to take the necessary steps to preserve east german 
jobs as the two nations negotiate the terms of currency union 
east german politicians are pressing for a general 1to1 swap 
of east german marks for west german marks but western financial 
experts continually have warned that could create high unemployment 
in east germany because it would increase businesses debts as well 
as their payrolls 
some forecasts have said 2 million east germans could lose their 
jobs under such a plan 
in their report the five institutes said strong economic growth 
in west germany over the next two years hinges on east germany 
scrapping its planned economy in favor of a freemarket system 
west germanys economic legal and tax systems will have to be 
adopted by east germany the experts said 
schatz said east germany will face enormous pressures during 
the transition to a marketeconomy system but he said those same 
pressures bring great advantages 
he said that after east germanys full entry into a 
marketeconomy system in a short time an enormous production 
impulse will be realized 
in addition east germans will have to pay far less for western 
imports then they do now he said 
according to schatz as east germanys economic health recovers 
that will provide a bonus for west germanys economy as well 
the economic reconstruction of east germany will lead to a 
high need for investment goods which without a doubt will be met 
for the most part by deliveries from the federal republic west 
germany said schatz 
he said east german demand for west german consumer goods likely 
will increase immediately after monetary union is implemented 
which may occur as early as july 1 
the economic forecasts were conducted jointly by the ifo 
economic research institute in munich the german institute for 
economic research in west berlin the rwi economic research 
institute in essen the institute for world economics in kiel and 
the hwwa institute for economic research in hamburg 
</TEXT>
