learjet corp the maker of small business 
jets favored by corporate executives will be sold to canadas 
bombardier inc for 75 million under an agreement announced monday 
the deal must be approved by a us bankruptcy court judge in 
new york learjets parent integrated resources inc filed for 
chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in february after defaulting on 
debt payments 
in addition to the purchase price a newly formed bombardier 
subsidiary will assume liabilities associated with learjets 
continuing operations including loans outstanding under the 
companys 38 million line of credit 
montrealbased bombardier designs and manufactures 
transportation equipment and motorized consumer products it also 
has interests in civilian and military aerospace 
learjet spokesman bill robinson said the deal amounts to 15 
million more than the last bidder had offered 
learjet was founded by bill lear in the late 1950s to 
manufacture business jets it currently makes three light jets and 
a medium class model selling for 38 million to 72 million 
learjet employs 2750 people companywide and has annual sales 
in excess of 250 million it was acquired by integrated in 1987 
bombardiers products include rail transit equipment 
snowmobiles and a heavy business jet called challenger jet which 
is manufactured by its canadair group and sells for 14 million to 
18 million 
the company has plants in canada the united states austria 
belgium france england finland and sweden and employs 22500 
people bombardiers annual business volume is more than 2 billion 
canadian 
bombardier plans to keep learjets current operations in wichita 
and allow present management to operate the business robinson said 
in late february another group that tentatively had agreed to 
buy learjet for 60 million let its offer lapse the group said at 
the time that the bankruptcy filing by integrated could hamper the 
deal 
learjet officials said other potential buyers had written the 
bankruptcy court expressing an interest in buying the company for 
more than 60 million bombardier confirmed it was one of those 
companies 
we are in the process of selling a significant number of 
assets prior to presenting our restructuring program to our 
creditors said stephen d weinroth integrateds chairman and 
chief executive officer 
he said the learjet sale will be the first major asset 
disposition outside integrateds former core businesses 
integrated began as a real estate company and expanded rapidly 
several years to become the largest seller of taxsheltered 
investments 
but the taxshelter business was scuttled by the 1986 taxlaw 
revisions so integrated moved into insurance and mutual funds 
financed largely through junk bonds 
