<TEXT>
chinas slumping economy recorded zero growth in 
industrial output during the first quarter although some signs of 
recovery were seen in march 
state statistical bureau figures reported in the official press 
tuesday also revealed that smaller township and private 
enterprises continued to expand while staterun enterprises showed 
declining output and productivity 
industrial output for march was up 14 percent compared to the 
same month in 1989 output in state enterprises was the same as 
last year while collectives showed 07 percent growth township 
enterprises 54 percent and others mainly small private firms 
323 percent 
for the first quarter the industrial output value of 
stateowned enterprises fell 11 percent to 2855 billion yuan 
607 billion and collectives were down 14 percent to 1116 
billion yuan 237 billion 
township enterprises however were up 35 percent and others 
by 304 percent 
combined industrial output in the first quarter was 4158 
billion yuan 885 billion the same as in 1989 
tough austerity measures aimed at curbing inflation and 
unsustainable economic growth brought industrial output growth down 
to 83 percent last year from 21 percent in 1988 
but in the past six months thousands of factories have closed 
down or reduced production because tight money policies have 
deprived them of funds and the suspension of capital investment 
projects have left them without work 
through february industrial output was down 09 percent 
compared to the same period last year the statistical bureau 
report said 
the government concerned about rising unemployment and the 
threat of recession has begun pumping money back into the economy 
but the bureau warned that despite the slight recovery in march 
the industrial outlook for the coming months remained grim 
it said productivity in stateowned enterprises during the first 
two months of 1990 was down 23 percent 
