<TEXT>
insurance companies are liable for 960 million 
in damage and injury claims against owensillinois inc arising 
from the use of its products containing asbestos a new jersey 
court has ruled 
the ruling is believed to be one of the largest surrounding the 
issue of who is liable for claims that asbestos made people ill 
the new york times said in its tuesday editions 
new jersey superior court judge erminie conly on friday issued a 
finding of liability against five insurance companies allstate 
cigna reinsurance general reinsurance united insurance and 
american risk management 
the case relates to industrial insulating materials the toledo 
ohio company made between 1948 and 1958 that contained 15 percent 
asbestos said andrew berry who represented owensillinois 
as a result of the production owensillinois is a defendant in 
thousands of cases brought on behalf of individuals and property 
owners who contend they have been made ill by the materials the 
times reported 
this is the latest and biggest of a series of decisions over 
the last decade berry said 
david daloia who represented allstate and united insurance 
said an appeal was under consideration 
the ruling appeared to be a setback for the insurance industry 
which had recently been on a winning streak in liability cases the 
times said 
companies that produced material with asbestos have been 
wrangling with their insurance companies for more than a decade 
over whether the insurance covers death and illness claims arising 
from longterm asbestos exposure 
insurers have argued successfully in many cases that illnesses 
from asbestos exposure have not been accidental events typically 
covered by insurance instead they have said the injuries were due 
to corporate strategies that knew the health risks but continued 
production 
